Skincare Product Description Guidelines for Shopify

Primary Goals:
	1.	Educate and convert real customers with clear, benefit-focused content.
	2.	Rank in search engines by matching real user intent with optimized, high-quality SEO content.

Critical Requirements
	•	Accuracy first: All information must be 100% verifiable from the official manufacturer source. No assumptions, no added claims unless explicitly supported.
	•	Skincare only: These guidelines apply only to skincare products (serums, moisturizers, toners, eye creams, sunscreens, exfoliants, masks, essences, acne treatments, etc.). Do not apply to makeup, hair care, body care, tools, oral care, or fragrance—those need separate tailored instructions.
	•	Language versions:
	•	English version is required by default.
	•	Arabic version is created only if (a) explicitly requested and (b) provided with the exact Arabic product name.

⸻

1. Process Overview
	1.	Confirm category: Ensure the product is a skincare product.
	2.	Keyword research: Build the English keyword list before writing. Include brand variations, high-intent search phrases, product type, skin concerns, and benefits.
	3.	Write description: Follow the structure below exactly, starting with the SEO-focused opening paragraph.
	4.	Supplementary SEO elements: Create Title, Meta Description, Tags, Alt Text, and Tips/Warnings based on the same source.
	5.	Review/verify: Run through the final checklist.
	6.	Arabic version (if applicable): Only after both conditions are met, adapt the content into Arabic following the parallel structure (not included here unless requested).

⸻

2. Writing and Formatting Rules
	•	Tone and purpose: Clear, helpful, benefit-oriented, jargon-light but with accurate terminology. Avoid fluff, vague hype, or generic adjectives (e.g., skip “amazing,” “revolutionary” unless the brand language uses it and it’s supported).
	•	Headings: Use bold (<strong>) only for section titles.
	•	Paragraphs: Default size; no manual font sizing or inline style.
	•	HTML structure:
	•	Use <strong> for headings.
	•	Use <ul class="-mt-1 list-disc space-y-2 pl-8"> with <li class="whitespace-normal break-words"> for lists like Key Benefits, Skin Types, Skin Concerns.
	•	Use <ol class="-mt-1 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-8"> for step-by-step usage if applicable.
	•	Use <br> or <br><br> consistently to separate sections for readability.
	•	No inline styles, no color definitions, no data-mce-style attributes.
	•	Keyword inclusion: Do not start writing until the English keyword list is complete and reflective of real customer search behavior.

⸻

3. SEO Keyword Rules
	•	Build a focused keyword list before writing. Include:
	•	Brand name + common misspellings/variants (e.g., with/without spaces, case variations).
	•	Product type (e.g., “hydrating face serum,” “non-comedogenic moisturizer”).
	•	Skin concerns the product targets (e.g., “dark spots,” “fine lines,” “dry skin treatment”).
	•	Benefits/results (e.g., “brightening,” “pore-minimizing,” “dewy glow”).
	•	Intent combinations: brand + concern, product + format + benefit (e.g., “Korean vitamin C serum for hyperpigmentation”).
	•	Avoid overly broad terms like “skincare” alone; prioritize mid- and high-intent phrases.
	•	The first sentence must naturally contain: brand name, product type, and at least one high-intent keyword phrase.

⸻

4. Description Structure (English)

[Product Name]  
[Before writing: complete and optimize the English keyword list for skincare.]

• Do not begin writing until the English keyword list is complete and intentionally reflects how customers search for this type of skincare solution.  
• Include the brand name and its common spelling variations in keywords.  
• Focus keyword combinations on brand + product type + skin concern or benefit.  
• Prioritize high-intent, descriptive phrases (e.g., “hydrating serum for dry skin,” “brightening vitamin C face cream,” “non-comedogenic acne treatment”).  
• The first sentence must include the brand name, product type, and one or more high-intent skincare keywords in a natural, compelling way.  
• The opening paragraph must be 80–180 words, explaining who the product is for, what it does, how it works (core mechanism), and what differentiates it. Write for humans first, optimized for search second.  
• Start writing the English description directly inside the code block without any extra heading labels.  
• This paragraph is the key SEO content — make it specific, benefit-driven, and keyword-aligned.
<br><br>

<strong>Key Benefits</strong>

<ul class="-mt-1 list-disc space-y-2 pl-8">
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">Benefit 1 (e.g., reduces redness and irritation)</li>
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">Benefit 2 (e.g., boosts hydration for plumper skin)</li>
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">Benefit 3 (e.g., improves texture and minimizes pores)</li>
    <!-- Add 3–7 clear, outcome-focused benefits -->
</ul>

<br>

<strong>Skin Types</strong>

<ul class="-mt-1 list-disc space-y-2 pl-8">
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">[Only applicable types: All skin types / Dry / Oily / Combination / Sensitive / Normal]</li>
</ul>

<br>

<strong>Skin Concerns</strong>

<ul class="-mt-1 list-disc space-y-2 pl-8">
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">[Relevant concerns, e.g., dehydration, hyperpigmentation, aging, dullness, acne, uneven tone]</li>
</ul>

<br>

<strong>How to Use</strong>

<!-- Step-by-step if applicable: -->
<ol class="-mt-1 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-8">
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">Step 1 (e.g., apply after cleansing and toning)</li>
    <li class="whitespace-normal break-words">Step 2 (e.g., follow with moisturizer)</li>
</ol>

<!-- Or paragraph if not discrete steps: -->
[Write as a single paragraph noting time of use (morning/evening), layering order, frequency, and any preparation/post notes.]

<br>

<strong>Ingredients:</strong> [List full official ingredients in INCI / Title Case, comma-separated, in the order provided by the manufacturer if given.]


⸻

5. Supplementary SEO & Conversion Fields (boxed code blocks, no labels inside)

Tips and Warnings

[2–4 actionable, context-aware tips/cautions. Examples:]
Use in the evening for best results when layering with retinol.  
Always apply sunscreen during the day when using AHAs.  
Patch test before full use if skin is sensitive.  
Start slowly with potent actives; increase frequency over time.

Tags

[Comma-separated, reflecting search behavior. Include brand variations, product type, concern, benefit. Example:]  
hydrating face serum, vitamin c serum, dark spot corrector, glowing skin, anti-aging serum, brightening serum, sensitive skin moisturizer, brandname skincare, skin tone evening

Page Title

[Brand Name] [Product Name] | [Primary Benefit or Feature]

Keep within 60–70 characters (ideal 55–65).

Meta Description

[140–155 characters; include brand, product type, key benefit or ingredient. Example:]  
BrandName Vitamin C Serum brightens dark spots and evens skin tone. Lightweight formula delivers antioxidant protection and radiant glow.

Media Alt Text

[5 variations, each under 125 characters, including brand + product + key feature. Examples:]  
BrandName Vitamin C Serum for Brightening  
Hydrating Face Serum by BrandName with Hyaluronic Acid  
BrandName Anti-Aging Serum for Fine Lines  
Lightweight Glow Serum BrandName for Uneven Skin Tone  
BrandName Skin Plumping Serum with Peptides


⸻

6. Categorization (for Shopify fields)

Shopify Category:

Health & Beauty > Personal Care > Cosmetics > Skin Care > [most specific subcategory, e.g., Face Serums, Moisturizers, Eye Creams, Sunscreen]

Product Type:

General short label e.g., Serum, Moisturizer, Toner, Eye Cream, Sunscreen, Exfoliant

Collections:

Use internal store structure examples:  
SKIN CARE > Serum & Treatments > Face Serum  
SKIN CARE > Moisturizers  
K-BEAUTY > Korean Skin Care  
ROUTINE > Morning Routine  

Include multiple only if truly relevant; avoid over-tagging.

⸻

